{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_start","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my careful review of the arbitration record and admitted evidence, I need to evaluate whether the proposition has been demonstrated by a preponderance of the evidence. The proposition requires that by May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\"\n\nThe evidence shows:\n1. **Public availability**: The SDNY order (PX-2) granted unsealing of the Note on May 6, 2026, and multiple news outlets (FOX Local, People, PBS/AP) reported on it before the May 8 deadline.\n\n2. **Credible reporting**: The sources are credible - FOX Local, People, and AP/PBS - and they consistently report that this was a \"purported suicide note\" attributed to Epstein.\n\n3. **Authorship and intent**: However, the reporting contains significant qualifiers that undermine the credibility of the authorship and intent claims. The PBS/AP report explicitly states \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found,\" and notes the note was absent from government death reports and DOJ file releases. The People report emphasizes the document was \"not dated or signed, has not been verified.\"\n\nThe key issue is that while there is credible reporting ABOUT the existence of a purported suicide note, the reporting itself contains substantial uncertainty about whether Epstein actually wrote it and whether it was intended as a suicide note. The market rule requires \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\" - not just credible reporting that such a claim exists.\n\nThe evidence shows credible outlets reporting uncertainty, not credible reporting resolving the authorship and intent questions in Epstein's favor. The qualifiers (\"purported,\" \"may have been written,\" \"unclear who wrote it,\" \"not verified\") are not mere formalities but substantive limitations that prevent a preponderance finding.\n\nBased on the preponderance standard, I find that the plaintiff has shown public availability of a disputed document, but has not shown by a preponderance that it was credibly reported as Epstein-written and intended as a suicide note/final message."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fa2e","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782798831706,"responseId":"gen-1782798832-NmYsppjt6fXRrjSrZ84x"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my careful review of the arbitration record and admitted evidence, I need to evaluate whether the proposition has been demonstrated by a preponderance of the evidence. The proposition requires that by May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\"\n\nThe evidence shows:\n1. **Public availability**: The SDNY order (PX-2) granted unsealing of the Note on May 6, 2026, and multiple news outlets (FOX Local, People, PBS/AP) reported on it before the May 8 deadline.\n\n2. **Credible reporting**: The sources are credible - FOX Local, People, and AP/PBS - and they consistently report that this was a \"purported suicide note\" attributed to Epstein.\n\n3. **Authorship and intent**: However, the reporting contains significant qualifiers that undermine the credibility of the authorship and intent claims. The PBS/AP report explicitly states \"It is unclear who wrote the note Tartaglione claimed to have found,\" and notes the note was absent from government death reports and DOJ file releases. The People report emphasizes the document was \"not dated or signed, has not been verified.\"\n\nThe key issue is that while there is credible reporting ABOUT the existence of a purported suicide note, the reporting itself contains substantial uncertainty about whether Epstein actually wrote it and whether it was intended as a suicide note. The market rule requires \"credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\" - not just credible reporting that such a claim exists.\n\nThe evidence shows credible outlets reporting uncertainty, not credible reporting resolving the authorship and intent questions in Epstein's favor. The qualifiers (\"purported,\" \"may have been written,\" \"unclear who wrote it,\" \"not verified\") are not mere formalities but substantive limitations that prevent a preponderance finding.\n\nBased on the preponderance standard, I find that the plaintiff has shown public availability of a disputed document, but has not shown by a preponderance that it was credibly reported as Epstein-written and intended as a suicide note/final message."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fa2e","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782798831706,"responseId":"gen-1782798832-NmYsppjt6fXRrjSrZ84x"}}
